segments.text: Fort Allbritton was a new member at that time.
All right, let's back up to coeducation.
Fort Allbritton was on in 73, because he was .
When the proposal about coeducation, non-compulsory core came up, do you have any idea what Mr.
Rudder's initial reaction was?
Do you have any idea whether he was for it or not?
Well, I would say Mr.
Rudder probably wouldn't have expressed his initial reaction.
I think Mr.
Rudder is going to think about it.
He's going to contact the QP.
I don't think he'd make a decision like that one way or the other.
I never heard any reports where he disagreed with it at all.
I have heard on English case he's the one that got people to make the recommendations to do it.
I don't know if that's true or not.
I've heard that he's asked several people to get the board
But he was a very good decision-making type of person.
He was the type of person that he maybe couldn't run all the alternatives through his mind at one time, but he could run enough through the decision that made him pretty healthy.
Let's see, let's go back to Austin.
Which governors were most supportive of the work of the Engineering Extension Service?
I'd say Dolph Briscoe.
Dolph Briscoe.
The reason I'm saying that, Dolph Cornell was several occasions for assistance in doing those things.
And most governors don't do that.
Other than local legislators, were there any other legislators that were key supporters?
Yes.
Who?
Senator Jones, on that one.
All right.
Do you remember his first name?
I don't.
Grant.
Grant Jones, that's right.
Any others?
Over the state?
Mm-hmm.
Well, of course, we had a lot of representatives, but I can't call their names right now.
But, yes, we, you know, wasn't.
I'll tell you how I handled that thing.
Whenever we had a budget, whenever they had the House Appropriations Committee, I made the point that each one of those people, not only know me, but know my programs.
I didn't work with the Higher Education Committee, but I made sure that everybody on the Appropriations Committee knew me.
And at that time, we all used to make presentations before they cut that out at the end.
They had this little representative from, I don't know, right out of Marlin Falls County, whatever it is.
He got to be a pretty good friend of mine, but that was 15, 18 years ago.
I sort of saw his name in the paper.
He's a lobbyist now, by the way.
Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.
Have you read any of one of those?
They all get to be lobbyists.
Yeah.
He was very much supportive of Trump.
Then we had a representative out of one of those Dallas towns, one of Cedar Hill, I don't know.
But he was a volunteer for us, so he was very supportive of us.
But I didn't do it really.
What were, as you look back, what were your proudest moments with the Extension Service, the highlight events that you now remember?
Well, I guess the highlight, the things that I remember,
enjoyed most about it was the ability that we had to bring about new programs to people in the state of Texas.
I was also extremely proud of the quality of our work.
I didn't get two complaints about our work over 19 years I was there.
I think we had extremely good people.

But my really highlights was I figured that when you take an organization with 15 employees and you end with 400 and you own a self-support base of a million and a half and you get it up to 39 million, that was always a good feeling.
And we carried, when I left that thing, you might be able to know, when I left that organization, I left over 13 million in reserves.
That's great.
Okay, now let's turn to the amusing side.
Can you think of some...

event that happened that was one of those Texas, unbelievable, something that maybe just went wrong, something just, the electricity went off, or it was one of those, I know you won't believe this, but it really happened?
Can you?
Well, I have one.
Okay.
I always had a State of the Union speech.
We always had an annual conference, and I always gave a State of the Union message, which I always stressed the basics.
And, of course, I had an information person who would always put my presentation together for me.
And I'd have slides.
And the last thing I always ended up with was a plate.
Well, for some reason, I had the damn button in my hand snapping up something.
And I was up there just talking like mad.
He said, Mr. Bradley, you're already on slide 20.
I wasn't even close to the one I was talking about.
In front of all 400 people, you know.
So they had a good laugh.
They all had a good laugh.
And of course, I come back at them, and I said, now, Clara, the reason I did that, I just wanted to see if you all were paying attention.
OK, now, from all of your Aggie memories, either as a student or employee, give me a funny Aggie story and then maybe a sad or poignant Aggie story.
It could involve anything, anybody.
Well, the saddest one, I can get that right off my chest in the beginning.
My roommate was in combat 21 days and killed.
And he was from Grange, Texas.
And I was in Fort Hood at the time, and I got called over.
Where?
And you all were roommates for how long?
Two years.
Two years.
Sure, sure.
Okay, now some good Aggie fun.
Well, I guess the biggest Aggie fun we had was in Texas,
The Thanksgiving game in 1940, we made the touchdown 7-0.
First 30, 40 seconds of play, and we were all hitchhiked into Austin.
And so my roommate at that time, also was from Ukraine, and O.T.
Rose, which was about five or six of us, was downhearted.
I had disgusted his life, I must say, with bitching him over.
But anyway, we got out on Congress Avenue and started hitchhiking.
We got picked up right off.
Two cars, one stopped, another stopped right behind us.
One had this Model A Ford with the little rumble seat in the back.
I don't remember.
I was in the rumble seat in the back.
And they kept going out to Congress Avenue.
You know, we told them, we want to get on the highway tonight.
And they took us out about 10 miles out of town.
And I'll tell you, there was 500 University of Texas people out there and about 50 Aggies.
And they would eat the hell out of us.
With a paddle?
No, with a fish.
Oh, oh, battle.
Oh.
That was quite funny.
The reason that was funny, you'd think you're so damn stupid that you'd get in a car like that.
And the other one pertains to your Rice University group.
Uh-oh, my freshman year, you know, we used to rent these cattle trailers to take us down to the courtroom.
And so our upperclassmen told us that they wanted us to
to all get together, freshmen.
There was a whole bunch of us to get together, freshmen, and have yell practice right there at the entrance of the rice gate.
Well, four of the five of us, we got out there early.
And we was standing there.
And all at once, about 15 or 20 of these damn rice owls come out and grab us, take us up to the damn dormitory room, and paint a damn horror on our head.
OK, let's see.
If you have any letters, diary, journal, or any personal items that you would ever be willing for the A&M Archives to copy, please do so.
Not asking you to give it to them, because you might want to keep them in the family.
But any time you have any papers that relate to your career, particularly as a student,
And or as an employee.
And if you have any letters that you wrote home from overseas.
If you would let me know.
Well, does anybody in the family have any?
I doubt it.
See, my family's all passed away.
Because I thought if there was any V-mail or anything like that.
I don't imagine so because my family's all been gone so long and their kids have everything.
But if you do, because, you see, if we can gather all of those materials up, the more we can learn about this school, the better we can make it go in the future.
The only thing that I've got that I don't know, I will go through my file.
I don't know, but I just went through the letters.
I've got the letters.
Every year, the letter that I got September 1st, now it's a little sour.
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
I've got that all the way through my career.
I'll have to look, but I might have some stuff there.
Okay, then the last thing.
In your heart now, as you look back, what parts of Texas A&M are dearest to you?
No, but what parts of the university?
But if I were to come to you and ask the engineering, any particular part of engineering?
Well, no, I think the...
I can't say about the last 10 years, but this is based on the last 10 years.
The engineering school at Texas A&M University, throughout the state of Texas, and I've traveled it all my life, both in industrial economics and .
They were known as problem solvers.
And people looked upon A&M's engineering thing as a place you'd come far to get a proper answer, not to get some damn theory.
And I was always extremely proud.
And I was always proud of the fact that they were all very professional.
I mean, they looked the part.
And I was always proud to say that I was from the Indian Country.
Always.
None of them knew me.
But I always felt that they had to respect the state.
Now, of course, agriculture has a strong, or it did at that time, have a very strong.
And you can see why.
Because you've got to eat.
And regardless what you think about agriculture, it's still an important segment of their economy.
But you've got to eat.
If you want an unhappy group of people, don't feed them.
So whether you like them or don't like them, you've got to respect them.
But I never, John Pierce and I were very close friends.
I like John real well.
Former dean of business.
Former dean of business.
I always felt that they could have, but Colt, he was the first dean.
Maybe he didn't have the resources, but I was, I wasn't too impressed with the college.
See, I taught at SMU five years.
And they had a, I was in the ninth college.
See, they used to get all their business school instructors from the Ministry of Mobile supported me to go out there and teach.
And I always thought that SMU had a much more effective school of business.
But now maybe that's changed.
See, I haven't been close to that.
All right, for today, let's stop.
And I want to thank you very, very much.
This has been a very good interview.
And whenever I can get a secretary, we're going to be hiring soon, get you a double-spaced first draft to go over and modify as you want to.
